items.name: SD 1.5 CineScapeXL beta
items.description:
Note: This is not an SDXL model! It's based on SD 1.5.

SD 1.5 | CineScapeXL beta1 is a bit of an experiment that focuses mainly on landscape and portrait images trained from SDXL - in terms of aspect ratio. Mainly cinematic style on higher resolution.

So you can use it on lower VRAM than SDXL and have (sort of) similar outputs, while also retaining the ability to merge the model with the broad range of other SD 1.5 models.

The model is primarily meant to be used with Automatic1111 and High.Res Fix. In my testing, I've found these settings to work quite well (many times you can also increase the initial resolution):

  • Most of the time I'd keep the lower aspect ratio at 512px (width or height depending on the ratio you want to use)

  • CFG Scale between 3.5 - 7.0 : Just play around with it. Sometimes the model tends to overfit a little.

  • The model will most of the time apply cinematic features to the image. If it doesnt, use something like 'cinematic style' 'greyscale' 'dark colors' 'photographic style' or 'analog film'.

  • Using (weight:1.3) on words works quite well if you miss something in the image or cant get certain style.

  • Generations of images at night should appear really dark, as the model has been trained with noise offset.

Important: Make sure to set SD VAE to None in Automatic1111 settings :

I might develop it further over time...

items.name: EasyFluff
items.description:
Results oversaturated, smooth, lacking detail? No result at all? Please read the following!

This is a terminal-snr-v-prediction model and requires a configuration file placed alongside the model and the CFG Rescale webui extension! See further down for more information and equivalent for ComfyUI.

HOW TO RUN THIS MODEL

- This is a terminal-snr-v-prediction model and you will need an accompanying configuration file to load the model in v-prediction mode. You can download it in the files drop-down and place it in the same folder as the model.

- You will also need https://github.com/Seshelle/CFG_Rescale_webui. This extension can be installed from the Extensions tab by copying this repository link into the Install from URL section. A CFG Rescale value of 0.7 is recommended by the creator of the extension themself. The CFG Rescale slider will be below your generation parameters and above the scripts section when installed. If you do not do this and run inference without CFG Rescale, these will be the types of results you can expect per this this research paper.

- If you are on ComfyUI, you will need the sampler_rescalecfg.py node from https://github.com/comfyanonymous/ComfyUI_experiments.

HOW TO PROMPT THIS MODEL

- Natural language has a strong impact on this model as of V7. It won't understand everything but it can get you places. And then when you can't squeeze any more out of it, you can use e621 tags to help refine your prompt. (or you can just use tags, either way will work.)

- Start your prompt with a short natural language prompt describing what you want, then pad it with e621 tags to refine specific concepts. As this is a v-prediction model, prompt interpretation can be a bit more literal.

- Many flavor words and artists from SD 1.5 work again.

- PolyFur is trained on MiniGPT-4 captions, so try being really flowery with your prompts and use sentences even. (check the generation info on the preview images to see how)

- If an established character isn't coming out accurately, try increasing the strength of their token and adding a few implied tags that describe their appearance. Keep in mind that characters that aren't very popular or don't have many images in FluffyRock's dataset typically won't fare that well without a LORA.

- Avoid weighting camera angle keywords too strongly, especially close-up.

- Resolutions between 576 and 1088 should work reasonably well as that is the range of FluffyRock.

Model Info and Creation Process

V8.1 now available. Last major version for a while. Currently the quality tag LORA from Feffy is not baked in and I recommend using it as a LORA. As of this V4-V6, @Feffy's Quality Tag LORA was baked into the FluffyRock part of this model. Add masterpiece, best quality and worst quality, low quality, normal quality to your positive/negative prompt.

This model is a "Train Difference" mix (see https://github.com/hako-mikan/sd-webui-supermerger/blob/main/calcmode_en.md#traindifference) of FluffyRock and PolyFur onto a diverse and versatile base model to expand the text encoder's range of prompting and understanding of concepts outside of e621 tags. This process differs from traditional merging and block merging and shouldn't be confused with "Add Difference" that we've had. The current base model is a mix of 6 non-furry models at varying ratios, which are mostly merges as well that cover a lot of ground in terms of prompting capability. As of V6 the process has gotten more intricate with CLIP tweaks and block merging.

Credits go to Lodestone Rock and company for training such an expansive model. https://civitai.com/models/92450?modelVersionId=124661 https://huggingface.co/lodestones/furryrock-model-safetensors/tree/main

And pokemonlover69 over at https://civitai.com/models/124655?modelVersionId=136127 for humoring my insanity on this process.

And Feffy for their Fluffyrock Quality Tags LORA. https://civitai.com/models/127533

items.name: Taylor Swift
items.description:
Due to Taylor's success as a youngling the base model training are tainted by too many young pictures creating a weird old/young affect when generating Taylor Swift images. So this Lora is trained on only recent images, a lot are taken from the recent era's tour.

Few quirks of note of this Lora:

  • In terms of clothing a lot of the training images included Taylor's iconic bejewelled leotard so even normal clothing is sometimes bejewelled or leotarded if you are not specific with clothing

  • Lovers of Taylors goofy smile will be happy as I made an extra effort to include a few in the dataset

  • Nearly every picture of Taylor has her holding a microphone, this sometimes pops up but is no worse than the usual AI hand qualms

  • Lighting plays quite an affect as it was difficult to find any natural lighting images but this just means you may need to be specific in this area if you don't get the desired affect

  • Makeup is not defaulted on images but trained in so do specify if desired

Any full body images, I fully recommend using aDetailer for best affect but nothing new there.

If you use this for NSFW images you will break my heart.

Trained on 1024 x 1024

I am still learning so any advice is greatly appreciated but this is the result of months of fun work!

Another day another update, this update improves generation quality and lowers the instances of 'fleshy furs' to the point that you no longer need to have "Human, Skin" in the negative prompt, and you can probably only include the furry tag in your prompt to get decent results. I've also started to incorporate sergal generation though its not perfect it does approximate pretty close.

Now, for the downsides. This model can no longer seem to do male furry characters, I'm not sure HOW that happened but I'll try and fix it and that will be the next version, in addition while this is still trained I did merge in another model, so I guess its no longer accurate to call this a trained checkpoint. In addition to being based off of BluePencil XL it was merged with FurtasticXL Epoch 3

As always please let me know if you have any promplems and I'll try to fix!

modelVersions.name: IcedCoffeeXL v1.1
modelVersions.description:
Changes:

  • Started from version 1.2 of BluePencilXL

  • Merged in multiple generational LoRAs, including previously used loras and three new versions.

  • Should be more consistent and allow for less quality tags overall

  • Can still perform well on multiple species, including sergal.

  • better reproduction of NSFW content, including more varied poses

Issues:

  • Still not a lot of male nudity, I'm still working on training a LoRA to merge in but so far its been very hard to reproduce anything.

Example:

  • Prompt: Stylized cinematic anime artwork, (fluffy anthro furry), Dingo, female, fit, digital painting, acrylic painting, (loose shirt, downblouse), side-tie bikini bottom, single tail, subsurface scattering, smooth lines, detailed

  • Negative: Blurry, poorly drawn, out of focus, (deformed, amputee, bad anatomy, bad hands, (skin, human:1.2)), extra limbs, extra tails, simple background

  • Sampler: I am using KDPM2 and DPM 1s and they work best for me in SDNext, but you should play around with what works best in your environment of choice.

  • Steps: 30

  • CFG: 3-9,

  • Resolution: 832x1280

  • Seed: 1597256910

modelVersions.name: IcedCoffeeXL v0.3
modelVersions.description:
While this is the first version I'm uploading its actually the 3rd version overall. I started by finetuning Blue pencil XL v0.0.9 for 2500 steps using 1000 high quality images but no tags, that got me closer so I trained a lora that I'll upload as well using around 150 high resolution and high quality images with individual captions and tags for 10 epochs at a batch size of 16 with 5 repeats then merged that into the model with a strength of 1. I've trained it on a variety of subjects and styles, so it can do quite a bit including NSFW Content and it pretty nails female anatomy at this point (though its still pretty bad when it comes to males, sorry guys I'm working on it). I recommend trimming back your tags from what you're used to with 1.5 models.

Example:

Prompt: Stylized anime artwork, (A female wolf, remarkably iris, detailed face), digital painting, pallet knife, photoshop acrylic painting, anime studio, subsurface scattering, HDR, masterpiece, best quality, detailed, absurd res

Negative: blurry, poorly drawn, out of focus, worst quality, low quality, simple background, deformed, bad anatomy, bad hands, extra limbs

Sampler: I prefer Euler A or UniPC they work best for me in SDNext, but you should play around with what works best in your environment of choice.

Steps: 20-30, it doesn't need much.

CFG: 3-5 will get you more creative/abstract stuff, 6-9 will get more precise. I've gone all the way up to 14 and it works but its really intense, you'll want to add in some negative quality tags like fried/overcooked/etc. For the example image I use 6.

Resolution: 832x1216

Seed: 244841152

I do not recommend clip skip or using the refiner (I haven't tried it, but it really doesn't need it)

Note that the terms furry, anthro, etc aren't really necessary as it has a really good grasp on furries, but you can add them to reinforce that, also if you find yourself getting smooth skin furries try adding human, skin to the negative prompt.

items.name: Aishwarya Lekshmi_Actress
items.description:
Use CyberRealistic epiCRealism Realistic Vision for better result

  • Use simple prompts. Complex prompts might make less realistic pictures because of CLIP bleeding. More complex prompts does not mean better results. Keep it simple.

  • Use ADetailer to enhance faces. Basically every solo portrait I made uses it. You can get my settings by clicking on "copy generation data". I suggest you use denoising under 0.3 to avoid getting always the same face.

  • Use BadDream and UnrealisticDream negative embeddings (BadDream, (UnrealisticDream:1.2)). Add weight to UnrealisticDream between 1.2 and 1.5. Do not use FastNegative or EasyNegative if you aim at realism. However, they're good for artworks.

  • Use Highres.fix with the following settings: Denoising strength: 0.45, Hires steps: 20, Hires upscaler: 8x_NMKD-Superscale_150000_G and as much upscale as you can (my gpu only handles up to x1.8 at 512x768 base resolution, but you can go higher). If you don't have 8x_NMKD-Superscale_150000_G you can probably use another GAN, but it should be easy to find on Google. You can also try Latent with a denoise higher than 0.6, but the result will be harder to control.

  • Try to condition faces by prompting for eye colors, hairstyles, hair color, ethnicity and so on. Even celebrity names do work. This model is pretty good at not making a single face if you play with the context.

  • If the pic is too clean, try to add some ISO noise. Even as a post processing with external tools it will trick the brain enough to make you think "damn, this is a real photo.

  • If you feel the grounded nature of this model is limiting your imagination, try generating on DS6 and then do img2img with this one to bump up the realism.
